<handout>
  <title>1.8 An Introduction to Linear Transformations</title>

  <!-- ==================== PAGE 1 ==================== -->
  <page>
    <title>Topics and Objectives</title>

    <objectives>
      <title>Topics</title>
      <ul>
        <li>The definition of a linear transformation.</li>
      <li>Interpreting matrix multiplication as a linear transformation.</li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>

    <objectives>
      <title>Goals</title>
      <ul>
        <li>Construct and interpret linear transformations in <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> (e.g., view a linear transformation as a projection or a shear).</li>
      <li><p>Characterize linear transformations using:
        <ul>
          <li>existence and uniqueness,</li>
          <li>domain, codomain, and range.</li>
        </ul>
        </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>

    <definition workspace="true">
    <statement>
        <p>Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m\times n</m> matrix. Define a function</p>
    <me>
      T:\mathbb{R}^n \to \mathbb{R}^m, \qquad T(\vec v) = A\vec v .
    </me>
    
      <p>A function of this form is called a <term>matrix transformation</term>.</p>
    <ul workspace="true">
      <li>The <term>domain</term> of <m>T</m> is <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.</li>
      <li>The <term>codomain</term> (or <term>target</term>) of <m>T</m> is <m>\mathbb{R}^m</m>.</li>
      <li>The vector <m>T(\vec x)</m> is the <term>image</term> of <m>\vec x</m> under <m>T</m>.</li>
      <li>The set of all possible images <m>T(\vec x)</m> is the <term>range</term> of <m>T</m>.</li>
    </ul>
</statement>
    </definition>

    <p>This yields another interpretation of the equation <m>A\vec x=\vec b</m>:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>as a system of linear equations,</li>
      <li>as an augmented matrix,</li>
      <li>as a vector equation,</li>
      <li>as a matrix equation,</li>
      <li>as a linear transformation equation.</li>
    </ul>
  </page>

  <!-- ==================== PAGE 3 ==================== -->
  <page>
    <title>Functions from Calculus (and their graphs)</title>

    <p>Many familiar functions have domain and codomain <m>\mathbb{R}</m>. For example, the sine function can be described by the rule</p>
    <me>
      f\colon \mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}, \qquad f(x)=\sin(x).
    </me>

    <p>In calculus we often visualize a function via its graph: the horizontal axis represents the domain and the vertical axis the codomain.</p>

    <image xml:id="img-sine-graph" width="80%">
